1 Filling gaps in lecture notes (10pts)

Consider the regression model \[ Y = f(X) + \epsilon, \] where \(\operatorname{E}(\epsilon) = 0\).

1.1 Optimal regression function

Show that the choice \[ f_{\text{opt}}(X) = \operatorname{E}(Y | X) \] minimizes the mean squared prediction error

\[ \operatorname{E}[(Y - f(X))^2], \]

where the expectations averages over variations in both \(X\) and \(Y\). (Hint: condition on \(X\).)

Answer: \[ \begin{align*} \operatorname{E}\{[Y - f(X)]^2\} & = \operatorname{E}\{[Y - \operatorname{E}(Y|X)+\operatorname{E}(Y|X)-f(X)]^2\}\\ & =\operatorname{E}\{[(Y - \operatorname{E}(Y|X))+(\operatorname{E}(Y|X)-f(X))]^2\}\\ & =\operatorname{E}\{[Y-E(Y|X)]^2\}+\operatorname{E}\{[E(Y|X)-f(X)]^2\}+\underbrace{2\operatorname{E}\{[E(Y|X)-f(X)][Y-E(Y|X)]\}}_{(3)}\\ (3)&=2\operatorname{E}\{[E(Y|X)-f(X)][Y-E(Y|X)]\}\\ &=2\operatorname{E}\{{\operatorname{E}\{[E(Y|X)-f(X)][Y-E(Y|X)]\}|X}\} \text{(Law of total expectation)}\\ &=2\operatorname{E}\{[E(Y|X)-f(X)]\underbrace{[E(Y|X)-E(Y|X)]}_{=0}\}\\ \operatorname{E}\{[Y - f(X)]^2\} & =\operatorname{E}\{[Y-E(Y|X)]^2\}+\operatorname{E}\{\underbrace{[E(Y|X)-f(X)]^2}_{\geq0}\}\\ \operatorname{E}\{[Y - f(X)]^2\}&\geq\underbrace{\operatorname{E}\{[Y-E(Y|X)]^2\}}_{\text{Irreducible}} \end{align*} \]

1.2 Bias-variance trade-off

Given an estimate \(\hat f\) of \(f\), show that the test error at a \(x_0\) can be decomposed as \[ \operatorname{E}[y_0 - \hat f(x_0)]^2 = \underbrace{\operatorname{Var}(\hat f(x_0)) + [\operatorname{Bias}(\hat f(x_0))]^2}_{\text{MSE of } \hat f(x_0) \text{ for estimating } f(x_0)} + \underbrace{\operatorname{Var}(\epsilon)}_{\text{irreducible}}, \] where the expectation averages over the variability in \(y_0\) and \(\hat f\).

Answer: \[ \begin{align*} \operatorname{E}[y_0 - \hat f(x_0)]^2 & = \operatorname{E}[(y_0 - f(x_0) + f(x_0) - \hat f(x_0)]^2\\ & =\operatorname{E}[(y_0 - f(x_0))^2 + (f(x_0) - \hat f(x_0))^2 + 2(y_0 - f(x_0))(f(x_0) - \hat f(x_0))]\\ & =\operatorname{E}[(y_0 - f(x_0))^2] + \operatorname{E}[(f(x_0) - \hat f(x_0))^2] + 2\operatorname{E}[(y_0 - f(x_0))(f(x_0) - \hat f(x_0))]\\ & =\operatorname{E}[(f(x_0)+\epsilon - f(x_0))^2] + \operatorname{E}[(f(x_0) - \hat f(x_0))^2] + 2\operatorname{E}[(f(x_0)+\epsilon - f(x_0))]\operatorname{E}[(f(x_0) - \hat f(x_0))]\\ & =\operatorname{E}[(\epsilon)^2] + \operatorname{E}[(f(x_0) - \hat f(x_0))^2] + \underbrace{2\operatorname{E}[\epsilon]\operatorname{E}[(f(x_0) - \hat f(x_0))]}_{\operatorname{E}(\epsilon)=0}\\ & =\operatorname{Var}(\epsilon) + \operatorname{E}[(f(x_0) - \hat f(x_0))^2] + 0\\ & =\underbrace{\operatorname{Var}(\hat f(x_0)) + [\operatorname{Bias}(\hat f(x_0))]^2}_{\operatorname{E}[(f(x_0) - \hat f(x_0))^2]} + \underbrace{\operatorname{Var}(\epsilon)}_{\text{irreducible}} \end{align*} \]

2 ISL Exercise 2.4.3 (10pts)

(a) Provide a sketch of typical (squared) bias, variance, training error, test error, and Bayes (or irreducible) error curves, on a single plot, as we go from less flexible statistical learning methods towards more flexible approaches. The x-axis should represent the amount of flexibility in the method, and the y-axis should represent the values for each curve. There should be five curves. Make sure to label each one.

library(ggplot2)
Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 4.3.2
flexibility <- seq(-2, 2, length.out = 100)
squared_bias <- 2*exp(-flexibility) + 2
variance <- 2*exp(flexibility) + 2
training_error <- squared_bias*.5
bayes_error <- 1
test_error <- squared_bias + variance + bayes_error

ggplot() +
  geom_line(aes(x = flexibility, y = squared_bias, color = "squared bias")) +
  geom_line(aes(x = flexibility, y = variance, color = "variance")) +
  geom_line(aes(x = flexibility, y = training_error, color = "training error")) +
  geom_line(aes(x = flexibility, y = test_error, color = "test error")) +
  geom_line(aes(x = flexibility, y = bayes_error, color = "bayes error")) +
  labs(x = "Flexibility", y = " Mean Squared Error", color = "Error Type") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("squared bias" = "red", "variance" = "blue", "training error" = "green", "test error" = "orange", "irreducible error" = "purple", "bayes error" = "black")) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")+
  labs(title = "Sketch Error Curves")

(b) Explain why each of the five curves has the shape displayed in part (a).

Answer: Bayes error (irreducible error) is flat because it is a constant and represents the lowest possible error of any model, which is the noise inherent in the dataset, thus it is not affected by the flexibility of the model and is lowest of any error.

The squared bias generally decreases as model flexibility increases. This is because a more flexible model can adapt better to the true function. However if a model becomes too flexible, it may lead to overfitting and the squared bias will increase.

The variance generally increases as model flexibility increases. This is because a more flexible model is more sensitive to the training data and will change more if the training data changes. A complex model would have high variance as they react to minor fluctuations in the training data.

The training error typically decreases as model flexibility increases because a more flexible model will fit the training data better. However, this may not translate to better test performance due to overfitting.

Initially test error would increase as model flexibility increases because the model fits better. However, past a point, the model will overfit the training data and test error will increase as model flexibility increases.

Answer:

One such useful application could be detecting phishing emails, then the user can be protected from phishing scams with email. The response variable would be the classification of whether said incoming email is either belonging in the category of âPhishâ or âNot Phishâ. The predictors could include email address, email content, attachments or other metadata of said email. The goal of this application is prediction, the model will predict the probability of said email being phish given the predictors.

Another useful application could be image recognition in autonomous vehicles. In autonomous driving, it involves classification with identifying the object in the camera of the vehicle to make the next decision. The response variable would be class labels of learned objects like other cars, trees, wall, pedestrian etc. The predictors could be pixels RGB values captured by the sensors or cameras. The goal for this particular purpose is prediction, where the model will predict the object in the surroundings captured by the sensors to make the next decision for autonomous driving purposes.

Third application could be diagnosis of diseases, this could report a specific possible disease given predictors. The response variable would be the probability of a medical condition and inferred presence of said condition. The predictors could be the symptoms and the medical history of the patient etc. The goal of this model would involve both inference and prediction, where predictions is involved with determining the probability of a disease and an inference would be made about the presence of that disease in the patient.

The response variable would be probability of lung cancer, while predictors could be the number of cigarette smoked per week, diet, exercise etc. The goal of this model would be inference using regression analysis to infer the relationships between different predictors and the probability of developing the lung cancer.

Another application could be productivity in the workplace. The response variable would be the productivity level of employees. 5 ISL Exercise 3.7.3 (12pts)

Suppose we have a data set with five predictors, X1 = GPA, X2 = IQ, X3 = Level (1 for College and 0 for High School), X4 = Interaction between GPA and IQ, and X5 = Interaction between GPA and Level. The response is starting salary after graduation (in thousands of dollars). Suppose we use least squares to fit the model, and get \(\hat{\beta}_0 = 50, \hat{\beta}_1 = 20, \hat{\beta}_2 = 0.07, \hat{\beta}_3 = 35, \hat{\beta}_4 = 0.01, \hat{\beta}_5 = â10\).

(a) Which answer is correct, and why? i. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, high school graduates earn more, on average, than college graduates.

Answer: Incorrect, since the coefficient for level (\(\hat{\beta}_3 = 35\)) is positive, this suggests that college graduates earn more than high school graduates.

  1. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, college graduates earn more, on average, than high school graduates.

Answer: Correct, since the coefficient for level (\(\hat{\beta}_3 = 35\)) is positive, this suggests that college graduates earn more than high school graduates by 35 thousand per increase in level (from high school to college).

  1. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, high school graduates earn more, on average, than college graduates provided that the GPA is high enough.

Answer: Incorrect, since the coefficient for level (\(\hat{\beta}_3 = 35\)) is positive at 35, while the interaction between GPA and Level (\(\hat{\beta}_5 = -10\)) has no effects on high school students (level = 0), it is inferred that if highschool student have the same high GPA as college student, a college student will benefit less in a salary argument. And with the effect of GPA (\(\hat{\beta}_1 = 20\)), it is still insufficient to offset the positive effect for a higher salary being a college student.

  1. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, college graduates earn more, on average, than high school graduates provided that the GPA is high enough.

Answer: Correct, since the coefficient for level (\(\hat{\beta}_3 = 35\)) is positive at 35, suggests that there is a salary advantage for college students by 35 thousand while the interaction between GPA and Level (\(\hat{\beta}_5 = -10\)) is negative at -10, this will reduce the incremental benefit of a higher GPA in college but there still is a positive effect overall with the effects of a higher GPA (_1 = 20) for a higher salary being a college student, this will make the salary difference in favor of college student graduates even more pronounced.

(b) Predict the salary of a college graduate with IQ of 110 and a GPA of 4.0.

Answer: We can predict the salary of a college graduate with IQ of 110 and a GPA of 4.0 by plugging the values into the equation.

\[ \begin{align*} \hat{y} &= \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1x_1 + \hat{\beta}_2x_2 + \hat{\beta}_3x_3 + \hat{\beta}_4x_4 + \hat{\beta}_5x_5 \\ \hat{y} &= 50 + 20(4.0) + 0.07(110) + 35(1) + 0.01(4.0)(110) + (-10)(4.0)(1)\\ \hat{y} &= 137.1 \text{ (In thousands)} \end{align*} \] (c) True or false: Since the coefficient for the GPA/IQ interaction term is very small, there is very little evidence of an interaction effect. Justify your answer.

Answer: False, the coefficient for the GPA/IQ interaction term being small does not mean that there is very little evidence of an interaction effect. The coefficient for the GPA/IQ interaction term being small only means that the effect of the interaction between GPA and IQ is small, but it does not mean that there is no interaction effect. The interaction effect is still present, but it is small. The evidence of interaction effect would require hypothesis testing and conclude based on the p-value and chosen significance level.

7 Bonus question (20pts)

For multiple linear regression, show that \(R^2\) is equal to the correlation between the response vector \(\mathbf{y} = (y_1, \ldots, y_n)^T\) and the fitted values \(\hat{\mathbf{y}} = (\hat y_1, \ldots, \hat y_n)^T\). That is \[ R^2 = 1 - \frac{\text{RSS}}{\text{TSS}} = [\operatorname{Cor}(\mathbf{y}, \hat{\mathbf{y}})]^2. \] Answer: \[ \begin{align*} R^2 &= 1 - \frac{\text{RSS}}{\text{TSS}}\\ &=\frac{\text{TSS}}{\text{TSS}} - \frac{\text{RSS}}{\text{TSS}}\\ &=\frac{\text{TSS}-\text{RSS}}{\text{TSS}}\\ &=\frac{\text{ESS}}{\text{TSS}}*\frac{\text{ESS}}{\text{ESS}}\\ &=\frac{[\sum_{i=1}^n(\hat{y}_i-\bar{y})^2]^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n(y_i-\bar{y})^2\sum_{i=1}^n(\hat{y}_i-\bar{y})^2}\\ &={\frac{\sum_{i=1}^n(\hat{y}_i-\bar{y})(y_i-\bar{y})}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(y_i-\bar{y})^2}\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(\hat{y}_i-\bar{y})^2}}}^2\\ &=[\operatorname{Cor}(\mathbf{y}, \hat{\mathbf{y}})]^2 \end{align*} \]
